    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-24T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-24T01:00:00-05:00" n="503"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d503">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker, Charles</persName>/39: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1" type="from">Adams</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-24T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 24, 1932—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 24—4:43 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>45. My No. 44, March 23 [<hi rend="italic">21</hi>], 4 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>I now learn that the National Flood Relief Commission has commenced dike
                        repair work in the area where <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                            >Baker</persName> was believed to have been captured, where he is
                        reported to be held now. This work is being carried on under arrangements
                        with <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s captors and
                        labor is being paid for with wheat. It occurs to me that if the Chinese
                        Government is persuaded to purchase <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                            >Baker</persName>’s freedom, as an alternative to the use of force, the
                        increase of wheat allotments in designated areas, under agreement with
                            <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s captors, might
                        procure <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s release.
                        The payment of <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s
                        ransom in wheat would not entail the outlay of any cash by the Chinese
                        Government. Food is needed in the area where <persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName> is held.</item>
                    <label>[2.]</label>
                    <item>I am reliably informed that negotiations with <persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s captors along the
                        suggested lines will be willingly undertaken by the local branch of the
                        National Flood Relief Organization provided the approval of the Chinese
                        Government is first obtained and appropriate instructions received from
                            <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SSJH1">Sir John Hope
                        Simpson</persName>, Director General of the National Flood Relief, 1C
                        Kiukiang Road, Shanghai.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Minister informed through the American Consul, Shanghai.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Adams</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
